               <p>GEORGE CLARKE. I am a <rs id="t18320906-263-viclabel1476" type="occupation">shoemaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-263-victim2154 t18320906-263-viclabel1476"></join>, on <placeName id="t18320906-263-crimeloc1477">Ludgate-hill</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-263-crimeloc1477" type="placeName" value="Ludgate-hill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-263-crimeloc1477" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-263-off1474 t18320906-263-crimeloc1477"></join>. On the 15th of August, about half-past nine o'clock, while my back was turned, these shoes were taken.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-263-person2155">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BROWN
               <interp inst="t18320906-263-person2155" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-263-person2155" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-263-person2155" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Whitmore-place, Hoxton, and am a shoemaker. I was in Mr. Clarke's shop on the 15th of August; he was busy - I saw the prisoner come in, and run off with a pair of shoes, which were two yards within the door; I pursued, and in Stationers'court secured him, and saw him throw them down - I held him, and brought them back.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-263-person2156">
                  SAMUEL 
                  COLLIER
               <interp inst="t18320906-263-person2156" type="surname" value="COLLIER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-263-person2156" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-263-person2156" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Kirby-street, Hatton-garden, and am a professor of music. I was at the top of Stationers'-court; the prisoner ran up the court, and Brown after him - I saw him throw down the shoes, and picked them up; he was taken, and I followed him into the shop with them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-263-person2157">
